  ],
  "buggy_functions": [
    "nfs_proc_getattr",
    "__nfs_revalidate_inode"
  ],
  "confidence": 0.85,
  "reasoning": "The bug is caused by incomplete signal handling in the NFS inode revalidation path. NFSv3 (nfs3proc.c) has a wrapper function (nfs3_rpc_wrapper) that checks for fatal signals and retries RPC calls when interrupted, but NFSv2 (proc.c) lacks this protection. When rpc_call_sync in nfs_proc_getattr is interrupted by a signal during RPC wait (with TASK_KILLABLE mode in rpc_wait_bit_killable), it returns -ERESTARTSYS. This error is then treated as a hard failure in __nfs_revalidate_inode, causing the inode cache to be invalidated. For autofs mount points, this cache invalidation triggers unmounting of the entire automounted filesystem, causing the mount to disappear. The root issue is that nfs_proc_getattr does not handle the transient -ERESTARTSYS error gracefully, unlike its NFSv3 counterpart. The fix should either: (1) wrap nfs_proc_getattr's rpc_call_sync calls with error handling similar to nfs3_rpc_wrapper, or (2) modify __nfs_revalidate_inode to retry or handle -ERESTARTSYS specially instead of treating it as a permanent error."
}

